value.value: A hormone producing or non-producing endocrine neoplasm, not associated with a hormonal syndrome.
A hormone producing endocrine neoplasm, associated with a hormonal syndrome.

A vascular proliferation characterized by the presence of prominent endothelial cells and the formation of vascular channels. Hemangioendotheliomas may display borderline or low grade characteristics.

label.value: Ewing sarcoma/peripheral primitive neuroectodermal tumor of bone

value.value: A spectrum of malignant tumors arising from the bone and characterized morphologically by the presence of small round cells. Ewing sarcoma and peripheral primitive neuroectodermal tumor represent the ends of a spectrum, with Ewing sarcoma lacking evidence of neural differentiation and the markers that characterize the peripheral primitive neuroectodermal tumor. Ewing sarcoma and peripheral primitive neuroectodermal tumor may share cytogenetic abnormalities, proto-oncogene expression, cell culture and immunohistochemical abnormalities. Pain and the presence of a mass are the most common clinical symptoms.
An characteristic of a disease that varies depending on whether the disease appears as an isolated feature or whether the disease is a syndrome consisting of multiple features.
An characteristic of a disease in which the disease is not manifested as an isolated feature but has multiple distinct features.
An characteristic of a disease in which the disease is manifested as an isolated feature.
An ependymal tumor affecting the frontal lobe of the brain.
An acquired coagulation disorder due to reduced levels and activity of factor XIII.

definition.value: An bleeding disorder with a decreased antigen and/or activity of factor X (FX) that is acquired. Acquired factor X deficiency is a rare disorder, commonly associated with a preceding viral illness and a circulating FX inhibitor. Although multiple treatment modalities have been described with variable success, in many cases, it is a self-limited condition.

value.value: Malignant neoplasms that either originate from the bone marrow (e.g. myeloid leukemias) or involve the bone marrow as secondary-metastatic tumors (e.g. metastatic carcinomas to the bone marrow). --2003
A characteristic of a disease in which the disease is present at birth, regardless of cause.

The acquired form of RMD. Although RMD most often is reported with autosomal dominant inheritance, some sporadic cases are found, and an association with other diseases such as myasthenia gravis has also been reported.
A benign, borderline, or malignant epithelial tumor of the ovary that is characterized by a predominance of clear and hobnail cells.
OBSOLETE. A disease that involves the genitourinary system.

Any disease or disorder that disrupts the process development of an anatomical structure. Can be due to genetic or environmental causes. Typically happens during embryogenesis, but also includes post-embryonic development.

A benign, precancerous, or malignant neoplasm that affects the female reproductive system. Representative examples include uterine corpus leiomyoma, endocervical polyp, ovarian carcinoma, cervical carcinoma, and endometrial carcinoma.
A characteristic of a disease in which the cause of the disease is a genetic problem inherited from either or both parents.
A disease that involves the dermis.
X-linked form of cone-rod dystrophy.
Inflammation of the pituitary gland.
An salpingitis caused by infection with Neisseria gonorrhoeae.
An cystitis caused by infection with Neisseria gonorrhoeae.
An prostatitis (disease) caused by infection with Neisseria gonorrhoeae.
An inflammatory disease involving a pathogenic inflammatory response in the prepuce of penis.

A malignant neoplasm composed of large cells with large nuclei, prominent nucleoli, and abundant pale cytoplasm (Paget cells). Paget cell neoplasms include Paget disease of the nipple and extramammary Paget disease which may affect the vulva, penis, anus, skin and scrotum.
A hemangioma characterized by the presence of epithelioid endothelial cells.
Classic form of Timothy syndrome, includes all features of generic.
Infection of the vulva and the vagina caused by herpes simplex virus.

Disorders caused by imbalances in the protein homeostasis network - synthesis, folding, and transport of proteins; post-translational modifications; and degradation or clearance of misfolded proteins.

Acquired xanthinuria is generally iatrogenic. Allopurinol treatment, administered to block XOR and prevent uric acid overproduction, leads to the accumulation of xanthine. Rarely, in the setting of aggressive chemotherapy with rapid tumor lysis or in patients with HPRT deficiency on allopurinol therapy, complications of renal failure can develop from xanthine crystal nephropathy.
Hemorrhagic and thrombotic disorders that occur as a consequence of inherited abnormalities in blood coagulation.
A disease that has its basis in the disruption of intestinal motility.

A benign or malignant neoplasm arising from tooth-forming tissues. It occurs in the maxillofacial skeleton or the gingiva. Benign tumors are slow growing and are not associated with specific clinical symptoms. Pain is absent or slight. Malignant tumors are usually associated with rapid swelling and pain.

A neoplasm of the nervous system that arises from the neuroepithelial tissues. Representative examples include astrocytic tumors, oligodendroglial tumors, ependymal tumors, and primitive neuroectodermal tumors.

An inflammatory process affecting the skin, caused by bacteria, viruses, parasites, or fungi. Examples of bacterial infection include carbuncles, furuncles, impetigo, erysipelas, and abscesses. Examples of viral infection include shingles, warts, molluscum contagiosum, and pityriasis rosea. Examples of parasitic infection include scabies and lice. Examples of fungal infection include athlete's foot, yeast infection, and ringworm.
A otitis media (disease) with a basis in a pathological type I hypersensitivity reaction.
Chronic form of otitis media (disease).
A disease that involves the ear.
Chronic form of non-suppurative otitis media.
An Crohn disease involving a pathogenic inflammatory response in the jejunum.
A neoplasm (disease) that involves the placenta.
A neoplasm (disease) that involves the vestibulocochlear nerve.
